                        <interp inst="t18390916-name-99" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18390916-2403-offence-1 t18390916-name-99"></join>William Ibbott</persName>; and that he had been previously convicted of felony.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390916-name-100" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390916-name-100" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390916-name-100" type="surname" value="MAYNE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390916-name-100" type="given" value="SARAH"></interp>SARAH MAYNE</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Bloomsbury-street. On the afternoon of</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183909160007"></xptr>
               <p>the 12th of July I saw the prisoner at Mr. Ibbott's, No. 13.—the window was open a little way, and I saw him take out a coat and waistcoat through the window—the waistcoat lodged on the window-sill, but he ran away with the coat, leaving the waistcoat—I opened my window, and called, "Stop thief,"—he dropped the coat, and ran away.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> She said I opened the window. <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> No, I did not—I was particularly asked that, and I said I could not say that he opened the window—I saw a person pick the coat up.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390916-name-101" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390916-name-101" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390916-name-101" type="surname" value="IBBOTT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390916-name-101" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM IBBOTT</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Bloomsbury-street. This coat and waist-coat are mine—they were in my parlour on the morning of the 12th of July, near the window—I was not at home at the time they were taken.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390916-name-102" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390916-name-102" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390916-name-102" type="surname" value="GRANT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390916-name-102" type="given" value="DUNCAN"></interp>DUNCAN GRANT</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable B</hi> 80.) I heard the cry of "Stop thief"—I stopped the prisoner, and brought him back to the prosecutor's house—the things were produced to me at the door by a woman.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390916-name-103" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390916-name-103" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390916-name-103" type="surname" value="IBBOTT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390916-name-103" type="given" value="FRANCES"></interp>FRANCES IBBOTT</persName>
                  </hi>. The coat was brought to me—I do not know by whom, but it is the one that was taken from our window.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> I had nowhere to go—I did it from distress.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390916-name-104" type="witnessName">
